Public Prosecutor v Liew Ser Kang
[2023] SGDC 89

Case Number:District Arrest Case No 901722 of 2019, Magistrate's Appeal No. 9171-2022-01
Decision Date:11 May 2023
Tribunal/Court:District Court
Coram: Brenda Tan
Counsel Name(s): Bhajanvir Singh and Phoebe Tan (Attorney General's Chambers) for the Public Prosecutor; Mr A. Rajandran (A Rajandran) for the Defence.
Parties: Public Prosecutor — Liew Ser Kang

Criminal Law – Offences – Criminal Force and Assault

Criminal Procedure and Sentencing – Sentencing

[LawNet Editorial Note: An appeal to this decision has been filed in MA 9171/2022/01.]

11 May 2023

District Judge Brenda Tan:

Introduction

1       The accused, Liew Ser Kang, is a 57-year-old male Singaporean. He claimed trial to one charge under s 353 of the Penal Code (Cap. 224, 2008 Rev Ed) of using criminal force on a public servant, Sergeant Sheikh Abdul Muzzammil Bin Sheikh Abdul Feisal (“the victim”), a Traffic Police Officer, by driving his vehicle forward and colliding into the victim’s left shin thrice with intent to deter the victim from discharging his duty as such public servant. At the conclusion of the trial, I found the accused guilty as charged and I convicted him accordingly. I sentenced him to four months’ imprisonment.

2       The accused being dissatisfied with my decision has appealed against his conviction and sentence. He is presently on bail pending appeal.

The charge

3       The charge that the accused claimed trial to read as follows:

You, are charged that you, on 14th August 2018, at about 7.50pm, along Corporation Road towards AYE after Boon Lay Way, in front of Lakeholmz Condominium, Singapore, did use criminal force on one Sergeant Sheikh Abdul Muzzammil Bin Sheikh Abdul Feisal, a Police Officer, who is a public servant, to wit, by driving your vehicle, a white Honda Accord, registration number SKW3402C, forward and colliding into the said Police Officer on his left shin thrice, with intent to deter the said public servant from discharging his duty as such public servant, and you have thereby committed an offence punishable under Section 353 of the Penal Code (Cap. 224, 2008 Rev Ed).

Background facts

4       The victim (PW3) was a public servant, attached as a police officer to the patrol unit of Traffic Police (“TP”) Division. On 14 August 2018, he was performing patrol duty on his TP motorcycle around the western vicinity. He started his shift at 1pm and his duty was supposed to end at 11pm[note: 1].

5       At about 7.50pm at the junction of Boon Lay Way and Corporation Road, the victim observed that PW4 Chua Chee Koon (“PW4 Chua”) who was driving a black Audi (“black Audi”) was not wearing his seat belt. The victim signalled to PW4 Chua to pull over along Corporation Road after the junction. PW4 Chua complied, and he stopped his black Audi on Corporation Road. This stretch of Corporation Road was a two-lane road towards Ayer Rajah Expressway. PW4 Chua stopped his black Audi in the left lane, just beyond the bus bay[note: 2], near the entrance of Lakeholmz Condominium (“the Condominium”)[note: 3]. The victim stopped his TP motorcycle about one car length behind the black Audi[note: 4] in the left lane and left its blinkers on. The victim dismounted and approached PW4 Chua at the driver window to inform PW4 Chua that he was doing a routine check. PW4 Chua alighted and both PW4 Chua and the victim then moved to the side of the road behind the black Audi where the victim conducted checks on PW4 Chua. PW4 Chua’s passenger, PW5 Lim Yi Jun Cindy (“PW5 Cindy”) who was seated at the back passenger seat subsequently alighted from the black Audi too.

6       The accused was a resident of the Condominium. At around that time, he was heading home alone towards the Condominium in his white Honda Accord bearing the registration number SKW3402C (“the Car”). He was driving in the left lane of Corporation Road as he would soon be turning left into the Condominium when he saw that a black car which was the black Audi had stopped in the vicinity of the bus bay and was blocking the vehicles travelling in the left lane and obstructing direct passage into the Condominium from the left lane. Vehicles travelling in the left lane therefore had to filter to the right so that they could overtake the black Audi to continue their way.

7       When the Car was at the head of the vehicles which were obstructed in the left lane, he sounded the Car horn which caught the attention of the victim who was engaging PW4 Chua. The victim signalled to the accused to overtake the black Audi from the right lane. The victim then saw the accused making a hand gesture at him. The accused admitted that after he sounded the Car horn, he made a hand gesture in the direction of the black Audi. The nature of the accused’s hand gesture was disputed. His hand gesture was what sparked the events that followed.

8       Upon seeing the accused’s hand gesture, the victim walked over to the Car to confront the accused about his hand gesture. When the victim was at the accused’s driver window, he directed the accused to reverse the Car. Instead of reversing, the accused inched the Car forward which prompted the victim to quickly position himself at a safe distance in front of the Car to ask him to stop. The accused continued to ease his brakes, moved the Car forward, stopped then moved it forward again which he repeated a few times. During the times when the accused drove forward, the Car collided into the victim’s left shin thrice when the victim was standing directly in front of the Car. For the second and third collisions, the victim fell forward onto the Car bonnet.

9       The accused claimed that he was not aware of the first “contact” at that time because it occurred below his eye level in the driver seat where he was not able to see. Notwithstanding, the accused admitted that the victim “paused” in front of the Car and the accused did not dispute the first contact[note: 5]. The accused was aware of the second and third contacts between the Car and the victim’s body because the victim fell onto the Car bonnet before his eyes. The accused claimed that all three contacts were accidental.

10     The entire episode as to how the three collisions occurred was recorded in the in-car camera footages retrieved from the Car[note: 6]. The footages captured the accused moving the Car forward and colliding into the victim thrice at the following timestamps:

(a)     19:51:26 (the first collision)[note: 7];

(b)     19:51:30 (the second collision)[note: 8];

(c)     19:51:53 (“the third collision”)[note: 9].

11     The second and third collisions were partially captured in the footages retrieved from the camera mounted on the victim’s TP motorcycle[note: 10]. The CCTV footage retrieved from the Condominium guard house captured the third collision partially[note: 11].

Issues before the court

12     Criminal force is defined in section 350 of the Penal Code:

Whoever intentionally uses force to any person, without that person’s consent, in order to cause the committing of any offence, or intending by the use of such force illegally to cause, or knowing it to be likely that by the use of such force he will illegally cause injury, fear or annoyance to the person to whom the force is used, is said to use criminal force to that other.

13     The Prosecution’s case was that the accused had intentionally used criminal force to the victim by driving the Car forward and colliding into the victim‘s left shin thrice when the victim was executing his duty as a public servant. In this regard, the charge against the accused was that he used criminal force on the victim with intent to deter the victim from discharging his duty as such public servant.

14     The accused denied having the requisite mens rea for the offence. He maintained that he did not intend to cause hurt to the victim nor did he deliberately use criminal force as per the charge on the victim. He asserted that the contacts were accidental and that at all material times, he had complied with the instructions given by the victim, and as such, did not deter the victim in the discharge of the victim’s duties, except when the instructions were impossible to comply with[note: 12].

15     Therefore, the issues before the court were:

(a)     Whether the accused had intentionally used criminal force on the victim when he drove the Car forward and collided into the victim’s left shin thrice.

(b)     Whether the victim was discharging his duty as such public servant when the accused used criminal force on him; and

(c)     Whether the accused had intended to deter the victim from discharging his duty as such public servant.

Evidence of the victim (PW3)

16     The victim had been working as a TP patrol officer for four years. His duties included enforcing traffic rules, assisting in road traffic accidents, diverting and controlling traffic as well as to conduct road safety education. If he needed to check any vehicle, he would ensure that the vehicle pull over at a safe place after which he would position his motorcycle behind the vehicle and leave its blinkers on to warn other road users that he had stopped a vehicle.

17     The victim testified that he was engaging PW4 Chua at the side of Corporation Road when he heard three horns coming from the Car. After that, he heard another horn. So, he waved forward to the accused twice with his right hand to indicate to the accused he could overtake from the right lane. That was when he saw the accused giving him a “no brain” hand gesture. The accused was waving his right hand in the air, near his right eye very close to his head, slightly above his right ear, in a circular motion back and forth. The victim understood the accused to be telling him that he had “no brain”[note: 13].

18     The victim decided to approach the accused to find out the reason behind the “no brain” hand gesture. He walked to the front of the Car with his right hand raised to indicate to the accused to stop and not to move his vehicle after which the victim crossed to the driver side of the Car. The screenshot at timestamp 19:51:14[note: 14] which was obtained from the accused’s in-car camera footages and produced below, depicted the victim walking over to the driver side of the Car with his right hand raised. The victim’s TP motorcycle, black Audi, PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy were visible in the foreground. At that time, the speed of the Car was 001km/hr.

19     The Car window had been wound down. When the victim was at the accused’s window, he asked the accused, “Is there anything wrong, Sir?”. The accused replied, “You are blocking the entrance.” In response, the victim questioned the accused, “Does it mean that I have no brains, is it?” The victim then asked the accused to reverse, “Sir, can you please reverse, please? I need to talk to you.” The accused was however not compliant because he started moving forward “concurrently” as the victim was telling the accused to reverse[note: 15]. Hence, the victim told the accused, “Please reverse before I chase you”.

20     Despite the victim telling the accused twice to reverse or else he would have to “chase” the accused, the accused ignored the victim’s instructions and continued to move forward. The victim therefore found the accused’s behaviour to be suspicious and decided to do a check on the accused to see if the accused had committed any traffic offence such as driving without a valid licence.

21     The victim quickly moved to stand in front of the Car to stop him from driving off while keeping a safe distance of about less than a car length and showed the accused a stop hand gesture. The accused nonetheless continued to drive forward and at timestamp 19:51:26 of the accused’s in-car-camera footage[note: 16], the first collision occurred when the front of the Car hit the victim’s leg. The speed of the Car was shown to be 001km/hour. At that time, the Car had filtered to the right lane[note: 17]. For easy reference, I have extracted a screenshot of the first collision and reproduce it below.

22     After the first collision, the victim again created a safe distance between himself and the Car by walking backwards while facing the accused[note: 18]. He also gestured to the accused to stop. A screenshot of this scene at timestamp 19:51:27 is produced below[note: 19]. The accused’s speed was indicated as 002km/hr.

23     Notwithstanding, the accused carried on moving his car forward and caused the front part of the Car to hit the victim’s leg a second time. The timestamp for the second collision was 19:51:30[note: 20]. This round, the impact caused the victim to lose his balance and he fell forward with his hands hitting onto the car bonnet[note: 21]. A screenshot of the second collision is produced below (in colour)[note: 22]. By the second collision, the Car had travelled to the right lane[note: 23]. His speed was 002km/hr.

24     PW6, Investigation Officer Bernard Chua Cheng Boon (“PW6 IO Bernard”), who prepared the screenshots[note: 24] during the investigations stage had initially thought that there were only two collisions consisting of the second and third collision based on his interpretation of the accused’s in-car camera footages. He missed out on the first collision. PW6 IO Bernard had therefore captioned the screenshot of the second collision as depicting the victim being “hit by (the accused’s) vehicle for the first time”.

25     Upon the second collision, the victim decided to call his ops room for assistance[note: 25]. After summoning for help, he again gestured to the accused with his right hand to stop and not to move and he also gave the verbal command “Stop”. This scene was captured in the screenshot below[note: 26]. At this time, the Car had apparently come to a stop because the speed was 000km/hr.

26     Next, the victim waved a few times at the accused to reverse, accompanied with the verbal commands, “reverse”. The screenshot depicting this scene is produced below[note: 27]. The Car was stationery then as the speed was 000km/hr.

27     At this point when the Car was stationery, the victim wanted to walk over to the accused to ask him to reverse but suddenly the accused started moving the Car forward again[note: 28]. The victim promptly tapped on the Car bonnet three times to indicate to the accused to stop[note: 29]. A screenshot of the victim tapping on the right corner of the Car bonnet is produced below.

28     Despite the victim tapping on the car bonnet, the accused continued to drive forward. The victim had to retreat to keep a safe distance between himself and the Car. He told the court that he was scared for his life as he saw the Car approaching[note: 30]. The Car then hit the victim’s left leg for the third time, causing the victim to lose his balance and he fell forward with his left arm landing on the front bonnet of the Car[note: 31]. The victim felt scared and traumatised after being hit by the Car three times[note: 32]. His left leg was also in pain[note: 33]. The third collision occurred at timestamp 19:51:53 as depicted in the screenshot below[note: 34]. By the third collision, as shown in the screenshot, the accused had filtered the Car back to the left lane and was veering left to prepare to turn into the Condominium. His speed was 005km/hr.

29     After the third collision, the victim continued to gesture to the accused to stop but the accused still drove “very slightly forward”[note: 35]. At 19:52:21, the victim updated his ops room on the situation and requested for expedited resources to assist him with a non-compliant driver[note: 36].

30     The victim told the court that when the incident started, the Car was queuing behind the victim’s TP motorcycle in the left lane. By the third collision, the Car had overtaken the victim’s TP motorcycle and travelled about the length of one lamp post. The Car finally stopped about two car lengths in front of the victim’s TP motorcycle. It had moved about three to four car lengths from its initial position where the victim first approached the accused at his window[note: 37].

31     The victim said that additional resources arrived soon after. That was when the victim tried to talk to the accused again, but the accused did not want to talk to the victim. The victim felt that the accused was very angsty towards him. The victim then stepped away from the accused to update his team leader about the matter. Someone had called for the ambulance which arrived, and the paramedics attended to the victim. The victim complained to them about the pain in his left leg, back, and neck. Subsequently, PW6 IO Bernard, division resources and the victim’s supervisors also came to the scene.

32     At 8.29.54pm on 14 August 2018, when the victim was still at the scene, he lodged the First Information Report (“FIR”)[note: 38] regarding the incident with his ops room through his communication device. In his FIR, the victim reported, “Case of Rash Act, TPO stopped 1 violator at left of 2 lanes for check. However another car stopped behind TPO saying TPO got no brain to stop along the road. While TPO asking the car to reserve (sic) the driver seem reluctantly and moved forward and hit onto TPO.” The victim explained that “TPO” meant “Traffic Police Officer”.

33     At some point, the victim rode back to his HQ base to return his equipment, changed into his civilian clothes, and returned the TP motorcycle. He also had to update his log sheet. By the time he finished his duties, it was 3am on 15th August 2018. He then left for Changi General Hospital (“CGH”). PW2 Dr Mathavan Valantina examined the victim who similarly complained about the pain in his left leg, back, and neck. PW2 Dr Mathavan Valantina diagnosed the victim as suffering from minor injuries[note: 39].

Evidence of the accused (DW1)

34     At the time of the offence, the accused was 52 years old and working as a sales manager. He had been driving for about 28 years.

35     On the day in question, he was on his way home after meeting a friend. He reached Corporation Road at about 7.45pm and was queuing behind a white car in the left lane as he approached the Condominium. He noticed that a black Audi was blocking the entrance to the Condominium. The traffic was messy and hectic because it was peak hour, and due to the black Audi, only one lane was usable and cars which were on the left lane had to filter to the right lane.

36     When the white car in front of the accused, belonging to his neighbour, was filtering to the right lane, he saw a vehicle coming from behind on the right lane, so he sounded his horn to alert the white car. The accused then took his position and before filtering to the right lane, he sounded his horn and gestured in the general direction of the black Audi, to indicate that they were blocking the way and causing heavy congestion behind. The accused demonstrated his gesture by pointing his right arm forward with his right fist clenched and right thumb pointing outwards in the general direction of the black Audi followed by a circular movement in front of him with his right hand and then using his right arm and pointing behind to indicate heavy congestion at the back (“blocking the way” gesture)[note: 40]. He denied that he made the “no brain” gesture as described by the victim.

37     When the accused started to filter out after giving “blocking the way” gesture, he saw the TP officer (the victim) who was standing next to the driver of the black Audi walking towards the accused and waving to the accused to hold on. When the victim was at the accused’s driver window, the victim looked aggressive and angry. He immediately asked the accused, “Is there anything wrong?” The accused replied, “You all are blocking the entrance.” The victim then accused the accused of implying that the victim had no brain. The victim next told the accused, “reverse, reverse, reverse” in a very harsh tone and threatened to chase the accused. The accused said he was nervous and panicked because this was the first time in his many years of driving that he encountered such an incident. He said he could not reverse because there was a car behind, and he did not know how or which direction to reverse to. If he were to reverse, he would hit the car behind.

38     In his state of panic, the accused accidentally released the pressure on the brake pedal and the car inched forward. Then he saw the victim walking backwards while facing the Car with moving hand gestures which the accused understood to mean that the victim wanted him to move forward slowly. The accused demonstrated that he saw the victim indicating with his right arm stretched downwards with his palm facing down towards the ground in a moving gesture[note: 41].

39     The accused elaborated that the victim’s gesture was similar to the gestures he would see at the construction sites where the traffic marshals or safety officers would stand in front of his vehicle and guide him by moving backward and using the gesture which meant, “Slowly, slowly. Move forward. Slowly, slowly. Move forward.” The accused explained that he did a lot of project development sales at construction sites, and these were the common gestures that he had seen.

40     Hence, the accused continued to slowly release the brake pedal pressure and the car continued to inch forward. The victim continued to walk backwards and then he moved to the centre front of the Car, while maintaining a close distance with the car. Suddenly the victim “paused” so the accused quickly applied his brake. He said that there was accidental contact and the victim “bent” onto the bonnet, but the victim recovered steadily to a standing position.

41     Next, the victim put up a clear “stop” hand gesture. The accused demonstrated the “stop” hand gesture with his palm facing upwards in a stationery position[note: 42]. Since the Car was already stationary, he stayed stationary. Then the victim gave the accused another signal while saying “reverse, reverse” at the same time. This was the first time the victim was giving the accused a verbal command after he threatened to chase the accused earlier. As for the hand signal, the accused demonstrated that the victim was holding out his right arm with his palm facing inwards and flicking his right hand a few times indicating a reverse signal. The accused said that he could not reverse because it was unsafe. If he were to reverse, he knew he would hit the vehicles behind. He did not know which direction to reverse to since the victim did not indicate the direction therefore the accused remained stationary.

42     While the Car was stationary, he saw the victim glanced towards the entrance of the Condominium and stepping aside, thereby creating a clear path. The victim gave the accused the impression that he wanted the accused to move into the entrance of the Condominium[note: 43]. As such, the accused started veering left slowly by releasing the pressure on his brake pedal.

43     Suddenly, the victim tapped on the right corner of the Car bonnet. The accused did not know how many times the victim tapped. The victim then started walking backwards while following the path of the Car which was veering slowly to the left, towards the entrance of the Condominium. The victim then made a swift, fast move to the centre of the Car and “paused”[note: 44]. It happened so fast that the accused quickly jammed his brake. Unfortunately, there was accidental contact between the victim and the Car, and the victim fell onto the bonnet after which he recovered to walking position. At the time when the victim “paused”, he was very close to the Car, less than half a metre away. The accused said he was shocked[note: 45].

44     Later, another TP Police officer arrived and told the accused to park at a safe place. The accused quickly parked at the entrance of the Condominium next to the guard house. They then waited at the Condominium entrance for the IO to come to the scene. The accused’s wife also came upon the scene on her way home from work while the accused was waiting for the IO.

45     When PW6 IO Bernard arrived, he first went to the guard house. Later he went to the accused who was standing beside the Car to ask for the SD card of the Car camera. The accused withdrew the SD card and handed it to PW6 IO Bernard.

46     The ambulance arrived and parked next to the Car. The accused saw that the victim was able to walk to the ambulance. The accused also saw the victim explaining and demonstrating what happened to his supervisor at the bus bay.

47     Subsequently the accused was told by another TP officer to go to the bus bay where he was placed under arrest and taken to Jurong West Police Station.

48     The accused stated that he had no intention to hurt the victim. The victim was standing so close to the Car and things happened so fast that the accused could not react on time. The accused also denied having any intention to prevent the victim from discharging his duty.

The accused had intentionally used criminal force on the victim

49     After considering the evidence before me, I was satisfied that the accused had intentionally used criminal force on the victim when he drove the Car forward and collided into the victim’s left shin three times. My reasons were as follows.

The victim had given clear instructions to the accused to stop and reverse

First collision

50     The accused claimed that the victim was aggressive when he approached the accused and in the accused’s state of panic, he accidentally released the brake pedal which caused the Car to move forward. In my view, even if it were true that the accused had accidentally released his brakes, he ought to have re-applied his brakes immediately once he realized that the Car was moving and not let the Car continue to roll forward, but he did not.

51     The accused also claimed that that the hand gestures which the victim used when he was standing in front of the Car just before the first collision were not “stop” gestures because the victim was walking backwards while moving his palm which was facing downwards in a continuous motion. The accused averred that these gestures were like those he had seen at construction sites which were meant to guide him to drive forward slowly.

52     The accused’s explanation did not make sense. The victim had used a similar “stop” gesture when he first approached the accused and the accused had recognized the gesture to mean “hold on”[note: 46]. The main difference with the victim’s “stop” gesture when he first approached the accused and his “stop” gesture just before the first collision was that in the latter, the victim had to walk backwards to create a safe distance between himself and the Car which was advancing towards him. The victim explained that he was gesturing to the accused to stop the Car to the best of his ability given that he had to quickly shuffle to the front of the Car from the driver window to stop the accused from moving off[note: 47].

53     Furthermore, a few moments earlier, the victim had just instructed the accused to reverse because he needed to speak to the accused . According to the accused, the victim even “threatened” to chase the accused if he did not comply. The accused claimed that he only heard the victim asking him to reverse and did not hear the victim saying that he needed to speak to the accused. Granted that the accused might not have heard those words, he would already have known from their conversation that the victim stopped him and asked him to reverse because the victim wanted to engage him for implying that the victim had no brains. There was no reason why the victim would suddenly want the accused to drive forward. As captured by the accused’s in-car camera footages, up to the third collision, the victim repeatedly instructed the accused to stop and reverse.

54     Although the accused claimed that he was not aware of the first collision until he watched the in-car camera footages, he knew that the victim was standing right in front of the Car with no safe distancing, yet he did not stop the Car. It was therefore his intentional act of driving the Car forward contrary to the victim’s instructions to stop which resulted in the first collision. Hence, he had used criminal force on the victim in respect of the first collision.

Second collision

55     It was apparent from the accused’s in-car camera footages that he neither stopped nor slow down after the first collision. At the time of the first collision, his speed was 1km/hr (see screenshot at [21] above). In fact, the Car picked up speed after the first collision as the victim continued to walk backwards to create some safe distance even as he gestured to the accused to stop the Car. That was how the second collision occurred. By driving forward intentionally against the victim’s clear directions to stop, the accused had used criminal force on the victim to cause the second collision whereby the Car hit the victim on his left shin again. His speed was 2km/hr. The impact caused the victim to lose his balance and he fell forward with his hands pressing onto the Car bonnet (see screenshot at [24] above).

Third collision

56     The accused stopped the Car after the second collision which occurred at timestamp 19:51:30. By then, he would have known that it was dangerous for him to drive forward when the victim was standing close in front of the Car. Yet at timestamp 19:51:35 to 19:51:36[note: 48], he could be seen inching the Car forward which prompted the victim to show the accused a “stop” hand signal at 19:51:37 accompanied with a verbal command to stop (see screenshot at [25] above). The accused agreed that the victim was gesturing to him to stop[note: 49] and he stopped the car. Between 19:51:37 to the third collision which occurred at timestamp 195:51:53[note: 50], the victim gave the accused clear hand gestures and verbal commands to reverse. The accused chose to ignore these clear commands. Instead, he claimed ludicrously that at timestamp 19:51:46, because the victim glanced to his right towards the direction of the Condominium and stepped aside, he thought that the victim wanted him to move to the entrance of the Condominium[note: 51]. The accused preferred to go along with his impression rather than comply with the victim’s clear and express instructions to stop and reverse. He admitted that he released his brakes and slowly veered left towards the Condominium[note: 52] which was a deliberate act.

57     When the victim tapped urgently on the Car bonnet three times, he was clearly indicating to the accused to stop. The accused claimed that he did not know why the victim had tapped on his bonnet. If that were true, at the very least, the accused ought to have stopped the Car to find out what the victim wanted him to do, particularly after the second collision which the accused had full knowledge of. Instead, the accused paid no heed to the victim and simply continued to pick up speed as he consciously released his brakes and collided into the victim’s left shin a third time at the speed of 5km/hr (see screenshot at [28]). I agreed with the Prosecution that the accused missed the point by emphasising that he allegedly did not use the accelerator as the crux of the matter was whether he had intentionally used force by moving the Car forward, whether by releasing the brakes or stepping on the accelerator[note: 53]. The accused had thus used criminal force on the victim in respect of the third collision.

The discrepancies in the evidence of the victim were immaterial or minor

58     The central theme of the Defence was that all along, from the time the accused made the hand gesture which was misconstrued by the victim as an offensive gesture, the victim had an agenda to frame the accused[note: 54]. It alleged that in pursuit of that motive, the victim had lodged a false FIR[note: 55] and given a false statement to the police[note: 56]. It applied to impeach the credit of the victim under s 157 of the Evidence Act on the ground of material inconsistencies between his court testimony and the underlined portions of his statement to the police.

59     I have dealt with the underlined inconsistencies/discrepancies in the victim’s statement in the table at Annex A. To state briefly, I did not find the discrepancies to be material or significant. I would like to highlight one specific discrepancy where the victim stated in his FIR and statement that the accused had verbally said to the victim that the victim had no brains to park down there and blocked all the traffic[note: 57]. The victim admitted that the accused only made a “no brain” gesture and that the accused did not articulate it as such. The alleged utterance led to a holding charge under s 6 of the Protection from Harassment Act (“POHA”) which PW6 IO Bernard drafted on the basis that there was a possibility of an offence being committed. The POHA charge was served on the accused on 15 August 2018 when the accused was in the lock-up[note: 58]. It was never brought against the accused after PW6 IO Bernard verified from the accused’s in-car camera footages that the offence was not made out. The victim who readily admitted to the inconsistencies explained that he had given the FIR and statement to the best of his ability. As I have elaborated in Annex A, I did not consider it a material discrepancy.

60     Given my findings that that the discrepancies in the victim’s evidence were immaterial or minor, it meant that the allegations by the Defence that the victim had given false evidence and was out to frame the accused were therefore baseless. It followed that the related allegations mounted by the Defence which were premised on the victim having made a false statement were thus unwarranted or misconceived.

PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy corroborated the victim’s evidence in the material aspects

61     PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy who were independent eyewitnesses materially corroborated the victim’s evidence that the victim’s gestures meant “stop” and “reverse” respectively. In this regard, I set out below the Prosecution’s succinct summaries of PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy’s evidence[note: 59]:

15 (a)    Chua, who was the driver of the black car parked at the entrance of the condominium, testified that the victim had first walked to the front of the accused’s car and gestured to the accused to stop. Chua also gave evidence that it was pretty understandable that the aforesaid hand gesture was a stop sign. When asked about the victim’s hand gesture at about 19:51:37 of P4(V1), Chua testified that he perceived this hand gesture to mean stop. Chua also gave evidence that he perceived the victim’s hand gesture at about 19:51:42 of P4(V1) to mean reverse.

(b)    Cindy, who was the passenger of the black car, testified that she saw the victim moving towards the accused’s car that night and gesturing to the accused to stop his car at about 19:51:26. She demonstrated the victim’s hand gesture as such—right elbow in a perpendicular fashion with his palm facing upwards. She also testified that she perceived the victim’s hand gesture at 19:51:37 of P4(V1) to mean stop and the victim’s hand gesture at about 19:51:40 of P4(V1) to mean reverse.

The victim was a credible witness

62     In my view, the victim was a credible witness. His court testimony was materially consistent with his FIR and statement. In particular, he narrated in his statement that the Car had collided into his left shin on three occasions when the accused persisted in driving forward despite the victim’s warnings to stop[note: 60]. The victim’s account was objectively borne out in the accused’s in-car camera footages and materially corroborated by independent witnesses PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy. The victim’s evidence also tallied with the sketch plan drawn up that same night at 9.30pm depicting three points of collision[note: 61]. The medical report further supported his evidence as to the pain in his left leg, back, and neck[note: 62].

63     In this regard, the Defence was misconceived that the Prosecution was required to prove that the victim was unusually convincing[note: 63]. The “unusually convincing standard” is only applicable where an eyewitness’s uncorroborated testimony forms the sole basis for a conviction which was not the case here: Public Prosecutor v GCK [2020] SGCA 2 at [87].

The accused was not nervous nor was he in a panic

64     The accused told the court that he was nervous and had panicked because this was the first time a TP officer had approached him to confront him for implying that the TP officer had no brains and then speaking to him harshly. He insisted that it was dangerous for him to reverse as he was likely to hit the vehicles behind. Further, the victim did not tell him where he should reverse to.

65     The victim clarified that he did not tell the accused where he wanted the accused to reverse to because the accused started to move off before the victim had the chance to do so. He had intended to go to the back of the Car to guide the accused to reverse safely to the bus bay behind. In his assessment, the traffic conditions were safe enough for it to be done. The Prosecution submitted that from the rear-view camera footages from the accused’s car, there were no buses at the bus bay when the victim instructed the accused to reverse. The Prosecution submitted that the accused could have and should have reversed to let the victim conduct the checks.

66     It was noteworthy that the accused did not voice his doubts and fears about reversing to the victim at all. He simply wound up his window and started to move off before the victim had finished speaking to him. If the accused had been so worried that it was a bad idea for him to reverse, he could have easily raised it with the victim instead of disregarding the victim’s instructions.

67     It was evident that before the victim approached the accused that night, the victim was already frustrated and unhappy with the congestion or obstruction caused by the black Audi. He decided to horn in that direction to express his unhappiness and show the “blocking the way” gesture. When the victim was at his window, the accused did not appear intimidated, nor did he behave in a meek manner. He informed the victim loudly and bluntly that the victim was blocking the way. He did not deny that he had implied that the victim had no brains, nor did he seek to clarify with the victim what the victim meant. Although PW4 Chua could not hear their conversation, he could see that the accused looked aggressive, angry, impatient, and seemed to be shouting[note: 64]. In this regard, I agreed with the Prosecution that the victim was speaking to the accused politely and civilly[note: 65].

68     Aside from being outspoken and having the presence of mind to wind up the Car window before moving off, the accused did not seem concerned even after he saw the victim falling onto his bonnet and knew that he had collided into the victim. Not once did he enquire after the victim’s well-being. He was calm and collected to observe that the victim did not appear to have suffered any injuries. Subsequently, after the victim had reported the incident and the additional police resources had arrived, when the victim tried to engage the accused, the accused was angsty towards the victim and did not want to talk the victim. There was no reason for the accused to avoid the victim if the collisions were truly accidental.

69     Given my observations above, I did not believe that the accused was in a state of nervousness, confusion or panic during the incident such that he was unable to speak his mind or understand the victim’s clear hand gestures and verbal commands.

The accused’s account that the victim was instructing him to move forward slowly was unbelievable

70     In my view, the accused gave a contrived and unconvincing account that the victim was gesturing to him to drive forward slowly. From the start, when the victim was talking to the accused by his driver window, the victim had told the accused to reverse the Car. At the window, he told the accused more than once to reverse. The victim also issued verbal commands along the way to the accused to stop and reverse. At no time did the victim verbally instruct the accused to move forward.

71     The accused stopped the Car briefly after the second and third collisions but otherwise he paid no attention to the victim’s commands to stop and reverse. Instead, he conveniently latched on to the fact that because the victim was gesturing as he was walking backwards to assert that the victim was directing him to move forward. I agreed with the Prosecution that the board meaning of the victim’s hand gestures to stop which the accused claimed to be moving forward gestures was not lost because PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy clearly understood the victim’s gestures to mean stop[note: 66]. It was unbelievable that the accused with 28 years of driving experience could misunderstand or misinterpret the victim’s stop gestures as move forward gestures.

72     Even more absurdly, the accused claimed that after the second collision, when the victim was glancing to his right in the direction of the Condominium and stepping aside at the same time, the victim was giving the accused the impression that he wanted the accused to move into the entrance of the Condominium which was why the accused started to veer left[note: 67]. The accused explained that he was not suggesting that the victim knew that he was a resident and therefore wanted the accused to drive to his Condominium. The impression that the accused had was that the victim wanted the accused to move to a safe place to park which would be the Condominium because it was unsafe for him to stay on the right lane.

73     There was no basis for the accused to form such an impression from a mere glance. As the Prosecution had put to the accused, the victim was not a statue, and he could be expected to look around[note: 68]. I would add that in the victim’s capacity as a TP officer on duty, he might also need to scan the surroundings for safety issues. I agreed with the Prosecution that it defied reason that the victim’s cursory glance between 19:51:46 and 19:51:47 towards his left should give the accused the impression that he was to drive into the Condominium whereas the accused was unable to discern that the victim’s hand gestures at 19:51:15, 19:51:24 to 19:51:29, 19:51:37 to 19:51:45, 19:51:58 to 19:52:00 were for him to stop and reverse[note: 69]. In my view, the accused was using the so called “glance” by the victim to his right as an excuse to justify why the accused was veering left (towards his residence) when he had been maintaining that the victim was gesturing him to move forward.

The accused was not a credible witness

There were multiple inconsistencies between the accused’s court testimony and his statement

74     It was glaring that while the Defence expected the victim to be completely consistent and precise in all aspects of his evidence and denounced the victim for lying and implicating the accused falsely where there were any slight inconsistencies, the same was not required of the accused. It failed to appreciate that the accused had similarly been imprecise in his own account of events and had been inconsistent in his evidence.

75     I noted that there were multiple inconsistences between the accused’s court testimony and his statement some of which were material[note: 70]. Let me give a few examples.

(a)     In his statement, the accused gave the Car registration number as SKW3204C[note: 71] when the correct number was SKW3402C. Consequently, the charge against him was originally drafted with the incorrect car registration number[note: 72].

(b)     The accused gave a different description of his “blocking the way” gesture in court and in his statement. In court, he demonstrated his “blocking the way” gesture by pointing his right arm forward with his right fist clenched and right thumb pointing outwards in the general direction of the black Audi followed by a circular movement in front of him with his right hand and then using his right arm and pointing behind to indicate heavy congestion at the back. In his statement, he gave the following description:

The gesture I used was first using my right fist clenched and in rolling motion to the front. After that I pointed to the left a few times.

(c)     In his statement, the accused stated that when the victim was at the Car window, the victim said to him, “You think I siao?” meaning that the accused thought that the victim was crazy[note: 73]. The accused did not testify about this in court. What the victim purportedly said was shown to be wrong by the accused’s in-car camera footages.

(d)     In his statement, the accused narrated that the victim “fell to the ground”[note: 74]. The statement was incorrect because the victim did not fall to the ground. The inaccuracy was repeated in the original charge against the accused[note: 75].

(e)     In court, the accused admitted that he was aware of two “accidental contacts”. However, he failed to mention in his statement about the accidental contacts and that the victim fell onto his bonnet twice. The impression he gave in his statement was that there was no contact between the victim and the Car at all. In my view, these were material discrepancies that went towards the charge and undermined his credibility. The relevant portion of his statement is extracted below:

Q7)    When your vehicle moved forward, did you know that your vehicle had hit the Traffic Police Officer?

A7)    No, I was honestly not aware. I did not hear any knocking sound. My car has a front sensor, I also did not hear any sound from the sensor.

(f)     The accused made no mention at all in his statement that he was moving the Car forward because the victim was gesturing to him to drive forward slowly. He also failed to mention the glance that the victim made to his right which led him to believe that the victim wanted him to turn into the Condominium. These were material discrepancies and were clearly afterthoughts. I produce below what was recorded in his statement.

I thought that now that he had move backwards, I can move forward, and so I move my vehicle forward again. This happened about two to three times I think, he moved backwards and I moved my vehicle forward.

76     The accused’s court testimony also differed from his cautioned statement[note: 76] materially. The charge initially preferred against the accused was one under s 337(a) of the Penal Code, Cap 224 for causing hurt to the victim by doing an act so rashly as to endanger the personal safety of others by driving his vehicle forward three times and hitting the victim on his left shin and causing him to fall to the ground on the third time (“rash act charge”). In his cautioned statement, the accused did not deny or dispute that he had collided into the victim three times. His response was to qualify his actions by stating that he had no intention to hurt the victim. In court, we would note that the accused’s version was that he had known that there were two accidental contacts, and it was upon watching his in-car camera footages that he came to know that there were altogether three accidental contacts..

The accused’s evidence was inconsistent with what was captured in his in-car camera footages

77     The objective evidence from the accused’s own in-car camera footages did not support his account of events. For instance, the in-car camera footages invalidated his assertion that he first realised the presence of the victim after he had made his “blocking the way” gesture (see [94 to 103] below).

The accused was an evasive witness

78     I agreed with the Prosecution that the accused had also demonstrated himself to be an evasive witness by either refusing to answer the questions or answering selectively. In this regard, I refer to the Prosecution’s Closing Submissions at [31] and [32].

79     For the reasons above, the accused was not a credible witness.

DW3 Zabidean Bin Selamat’s evidence was unreliable

80     DW3 Zabidean Bin Selamat (“DW3 Zabidean”) was the security supervisor of the Condominium. He was on duty on 14th of August 2018 from 8:00am to 8:00pm. At about 7.30 plus pm when it was peak hour traffic, he was stationed just in front of the barrier entrance of the Condominium to ensure smooth traffic for the residents coming in and going out.

81     He saw a black car (the black Audi) parked along Corporation Road near the entrance of the Condominium. When he went closer, he saw that there was a TP motorcycle parked behind the black car. He assumed that the black car got into problem with the Traffic Police. He shouted to the TP officer (the victim) from afar not to let the black car block the entrance, but to ask the black car to move forward to after the entrance so that the vehicles from the residents could enter smoothly. But the victim seemed busy. At that time, the driver of the black car was still inside his car. DW3 then returned to his post.

82     A few minutes later, he heard a few car horns from behind the black car. He approached the black car again and that was when he saw the Car coming in. He recognized the accused as a resident. He saw that the victim was assisting and guiding the accused to move the Car from the right lane to the left lane to go left towards the Condominium entrance and that the Car was moving very slowly, slower than the people walking.

83     DW3 saw the victim standing in front of the Car and moving backwards slowly. He was surprised when the victim suddenly went in front of the Car and jumped onto the accused’s car bonnet. In DW3’s view, the victim was faking an accident. DW3 then approached the victim and when he was four steps away, he told the victim, “Sir, excuse me. Sir. Don’t wayang, lah, Sir.” He explained that “Wayang” meant in Malay that the victim was trying to create some fake things. The victim did not say anything. He looked at DW3 and seemed very angry.

84     After that, DW3 went to his guard post and tried to view the CCTV footage to see if he could find evidence of the victim’s wrongdoing. He was very sure that the victim was up to something funny and that the victim was trying to fake an accident. Unfortunately, the CCTV could not be played because the management had changed the password.

85     I did not find DW3 to be a reliable or objective witness. Unlike PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy who saw the entire episode, DW3 only witnessed the third collision from behind the victim. Yet he hastily jumped to the conclusions that a) the victim was guiding the accused to move the Car forward slowly to the entrance of the Condominium because traffic was piling up and the victim was trying to ease the congestion[note: 77] and b) that the victim was faking an accident because there was no collision. I agreed with the Prosecution that DW3 was fallacious in his assumption that there was no collision because the Defence agreed that there was a third point of contact (ie the third collision) between the victim and the Car which was what DW3 described as the wayang incident[note: 78]. DW3 also assumed that because the victim did not fall to the ground, he was not injured.

86     I noted that DW3 testified as to his confusion over he saw. He thought that the victim was helping to guide the accused to move the Car forward to lessen the traffic congestion. Therefore, he felt confused when he saw the victim throwing his body onto the bonnet[note: 79]. In my view, DW3’s confusion arose due to his erroneous presumption that the victim was gesturing to the accused to move forward so he could not reconcile why the victim would then “jump” onto the Car bonnet.

87     DW3’s tendency to presume was also apparent from two other instances. He presumed that the victim had heard him shouting from afar from the Condominium premises to ask the black Audi car to move away. He also assumed that the victim had heard his remark “not to wayang” because the victim had looked in his direction although they did not have eye contact[note: 80]. During the victim’s cross-examination, he told the court that he did not remember hearing those words. It would not be surprising if the victim did not hear what DW3 said to him that night. The victim was initially busy attending to PW4 Chua’s case and by the time DW3 allegedly made the wayang remark, the victim had been involved in three collisions and his immediate focus after the third collision was unlikely to be on the bystanders.

88     I noted that even after DW3 had watched the accused’s in-car camera footages in court and had the full picture of what had transpired, he insisted that the third collision or contact did not take place and that the victim was faking an accident, which was not the case for the Defence. His objectivity was further called into question.

89     I therefore attached little if no weight to DW3’s evidence.

The victim was discharging his duty as a public servant when the accused used criminal force on him

90     The victim was conducting checks on PW4 Chua and discharging his duty as a TP officer when he saw the accused showing him a “vulgar” “no brain” gesture which hurt the victim’s feelings. In my view, the victim was entitled to call the accused out on his insulting/abusive behaviour towards an enforcement officer who was merely performing his duty, which the victim did. The victim approached the accused and told him to reverse the Car as the victim needed to talk to him. When the accused showed no sign of complying with the victim’s instructions and instead started to move the Car forward, the victim became suspicious and decided to conduct a check on the accused to see if the accused had committed any traffic offence. I agreed with the Prosecution that the victim was acting within his powers as a public servant under s 127(4) of the Road Traffic Act 1961 (“RTA”) to stop any motor vehicle the driver of which had committed or was suspected of having committed an offence under the RTA or the rules.

91     The victim was thus discharging his duty as a public servant at the material time when the accused used criminal force on him by driving forward and colliding into his left shin three times. In this regard, I agreed with the Prosecution which submitted as follows[note: 81]:

(a)    First, contrary to the accused’s allegation that the victim told him harshly to reverse, the accused’s in-car camera footage shows that the victim spoke in a polite and civil manner.

(b)    Second, the victim was performing his duty as a traffic police officer and stopping Cindy and Chua for a check. Even if there were really a traffic congestion due to the victim’s checks, it cannot be held against the victim for performing his duty. It is certainly not a reason for the accused to drive forward and hit the victim with his car not just once, but thrice especially when the victim had told the accused that he needed to talk to him.

The accused had intended to deter the victim from discharging his duty as such public servant.

92     The evidence showed that the accused repeatedly refused to stop and reverse despite clear instructions from the victim. The accused had thus intended to deter the victim from discharging his duty as a public servant to stop the accused’s vehicle when the victim suspected that the accused may have committed an offence under the RTA.

Other significant issues that did not relate directly to the charge

93     For completeness, I shall also deal with the following issues.

The “no brain” gesture v “blocking the way” gesture

94     Although the disputed gesture made by the accused did not go towards the charge, as it was the triggering event, for completeness, I shall deal with it.

95     According to the accused, before he filtered out to the right lane, at timestamp 19:51:03, he horned and then gestured in the direction of the black Audi to make the point that they were obstructing traffic. He claimed that he was not aware of the presence of the victim until after he had made his gesture”[note: 82]. He also claimed that he did not see the victim waving him on between 19:51:09 to 19:51:11 to overtake the black Audi because he had turned to his right and was concentrating on filtering out. Without the help of his in-car camera footages, he would not have known that the victim had indicated to him to filter out. Therefore, according to the accused’s court testimony, he did not realize that he was gesturing to a TP officer.

96     It would be pertinent to note the accused’s in-car camera footage[note: 83] contradicted his evidence that he only became aware of the victim’s presence after the accused had made his gesture. The footage showed that when the accused sounded his horn at 19:51:03[note: 84], there was nothing hindering his view. He could not have missed seeing the victim’s TP motorcycle which had its blinkers on and the victim who was wearing his TP uniform and helmet. After the accused sounded his horn, his in-car camera footage showed the victim looking in the accused’s direction and waving him on twice. The victim told the court that he made eye contact with the accused during the wave on and the accused was looking at the victim when the accused made the no brain gesture[note: 85].

97     Interestingly, the learned Defence counsel had put to the victim that the accused made his gesture between the time when the victim was waving him on and the time when the victim started to approach the Car[note: 86]. The put was consistent with the victim’s evidence and what was captured in the in-car camera footage.

98     In my view, the evidence showed that when the accused sounded his horn, he was aware of the presence of the victim and when he made the gesture, he had intended the gesture for the victim.

99     The accused demonstrated his “blocking the way” gesture by pointing his right arm forward with his right fist clenched and right thumb pointing outwards in the general direction of the black Audi followed by a circular movement in front of him with his right hand and then using his right arm and pointing behind to indicate heavy congestion at the back.

100    The victim clarified that the “no brain” gesture which he saw should be the gesture as described in his statement which was recorded on the very day. The correct gesture involved the accused pointing his right index finger to his right temple, after which he used his right palm and wave it in a horizontal motion[note: 87].

101    PW4 Chua who saw the accused’s gesture, said that the accused lifted his right hand in a perpendicular manner, upwards above his head[note: 88]. PW4 Chua thought that the accused’s hand gesture meant “blocking my way”[note: 89]. PW5 Cindy said that she saw the accused raising his right elbow in a perpendicular manner with his palm facing upwards above the head. She thought the accused’s gesture probably mean, “eh why are you blocking up the way?”

102    Both PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy gave a similar description of the accused’s gesture. Their descriptions were closer to the victim’s description of the “no brain” gesture which involved holding the right hand with palm open around the head area than the accused’s “blocking the way” which involved a clenched fist and moving the right hand or arm forward and then backwards. I was therefore inclined to find that the victim who was looking at the accused and waving him on saw the accused making the “no brain” gesture clearly. He felt strongly enough about the “no brain” gesture to leave PW4 Chua’s case for the time being, to walk over to confront the accused about it.

103    My finding that the accused had made a “no brain” gesture at the victim was reinforced by the accused’s reactions when the victim was at the Car window. To recapitulate, the victim asked the accused, “Is there anything wrong, Sir?”. To which the accused replied, “You are blocking the entrance.” The victim then asked, “Does it mean that I have no brains, is it?” followed by “Sir, can you please reverse, please? I need to talk to you” and “Please reverse before I chase you”. The accused did not seem surprised by the victim’s remark that he was implying that the victim had no brains, nor did he deny the implication. He simply disengaged from the conversation by winding up his window[note: 90].

Whether PW6 IO Bernard met PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy at the scene

104    According to the evidence of PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy, after the incident, the victim approached them and asked if they could be his witnesses and they agreed. The victim took down their particulars and said that an officer might be calling them down to give a statement. The victim then told PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy that they could leave. Both of them told the court that they did not meet PW6 IO Bernard at the scene.

105    On the other hand, PW6 IO Bernard testified that he met both PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy at the scene and told them that he would be arranging for them to give their statements at the station.

106    The question arose as to whether PW6 IO Bernard had met PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy at the scene. In this regard, PW7 Sgt Ng Wei Lin (“PW7 Sgt Ng”) who was the Responding Officer, testified that he was deployed by the Ops room, and he and his partner reached the scene within ten minutes. PW6 IO Bernard arrived later. PW7 Sgt Ng did not recall seeing a black Audi and he was not aware of the presence of PW4 and PW5.

107    The Condominium CCTV footage captured the black Audi leaving the scene within five minutes after the incident which was consistent with the evidence of PW4 and PW5 that they left shortly after they had provided their particulars to the victim.

108    Having regard to the evidence above, PW6 IO Bernard could have mixed up the facts and was mistaken that he had met PW4 Chua and PW5 and the scene and spoken to them. Be that as it may, it was inconsequential whether PW6 IO Bernard met them at the scene or not.

PW6 IO Bernard’s failure to identify DW3 Zabidean as a witness.

109    The Defence alleged that PW6 IO Bernard had been biased in his investigations on various fronts. One of the allegations pertained to his failure to locate DW3 Zabidean as a material eyewitness when DW3 Zabidean had featured in the video footages.

110    PW6 IO Bernard testified that he would have received the call from the Ops room after 8.29pm, which was when the FIR was created. He reached the scene about 15 to 20 minutes, around 8.45pm to 8.50pm. Upon arrival, he met PW7 Sgt Ng who updated him on the case. PW6 IO Bernard then went about ascertaining if there were any video footages in the immediate vicinity. After that, he went around the immediate vicinity to look for witnesses. He found two witnesses namely PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy. He had also asked the security officers he had spoken to whether they had witnessed the incident, but no one came forward.

111    DW3 Zabidean testified that one civilian officer spoke to him and asked to review the CCTV footage. DW3 Zabidean referred the officer to the Condominium manager. Thereafter, he did not know what happened as his shift was supposed to end at 8pm but he was delayed due to queries from the management about the incident and he also had to put up an incident report. By the time he finished his shift, it was almost 9pm. DW3 Zabidean said that no officer had approached him to be a witness in this case.

112    PW6 IO Bernard arrived the scene at about 8.45pm to 8.50pm and ten to 15 minutes later, DW3 Zabidean ended his shift. In my view, it was possible that by the time PW6 IO Bernard went around looking for eyewitnesses, DW3 Zabidean had already left the premises and it was a lost opportunity for both of them. In this regard, I agreed with the Prosecution that just because PW6 IO Bernard missed out on Zabidean as a witness did not mean that there was any impropriety involved.

PW6 IO Bernard testified having seen the victim falling onto the Car bonnet in the Condominium CCTV footage but it was not captured in the footage

113    PW6 IO Bernard testified that he managed to view the Condominium CCTV footage when he was at the guard house, and he told the court that it showed the victim being hit by the Car and the victim falling onto the bonnet. The part where the victim fell onto the bonnet during the third collision was not captured within the frame of the footage. I agreed that PW6 IO Bernard had given inconsistent evidence in this regard. Since he had watched the accused’s in-car camera footages subsequently, his memory could have been influenced and led to his inaccurate recollections. Nevertheless, he did not fabricate the evidence because the third collision was real, and it was true that victim fell onto the bonnet.

Remaining issues raised by the Defence

114    The Defence canvassed numerous other issues which were unsubstantiated, immaterial or did not go towards the elements of the charge[note: 91]. For instance, it made allegations of biased investigations and tailoring of evidence by the Prosecution witnesses to the accused’s in-car camera footages. It also submitted at length on every minute omission in the Prosecution’s “Summary of Facts” which was not tendered in court or referred to during the trial. Suffice it for me to say that I agreed with the Prosecution’s submissions in respect of these matters.

Section 126 of the Evidence Act

115    I should mention that during the trial, the Defence subpoenaed the Commanding Officer (CO) of the TP Patrol Unit to testify on a) whether TP had any Standard Operating Procedures (SOPs) that governed how the victim should have engaged the accused at the material time, b) if the SOPs existed, whether the victim was acting in accordance with the SOPs, and c) whether any action was taken against the victim for making a false statement to the IO on 14 August 2018 at 11.18 pm regarding the incident. The Attorney General’s Chambers (AGC) which represented TP and the CO appeared in court on their behalf and objected to evidence being adduced for (b) and (c) as it pertained to protected official communications under s 126 of the Evidence besides being irrelevant.

116    I had provided my brief remarks and gave my ruling after hearing submissions from AGC and the Defence[note: 92]. My brief remarks and ruling are produced below.

The Defence has obtained a subpoena for Supt Tan, the commanding officer of the Traffic Police Patrol Unit, to give evidence in this trial against Mr. Liew on 3 queries which I will refer to as queries (a) to (c). AGC, which is representing the Traffic Police and Supt Tan, initially applied to cancel or to discharge the summons to compel Supt Tan to give evidence in this Court. AGC has since taken the position that it has no objection to query (a) but objects to evidence being adduced from Supt Tan in respect of queries (b) and (c) on the grounds that the information is not relevant or necessary for the current criminal proceedings and that it is also protected by section 126 of the Evidence Act.

In my view, there can be no doubt that the information requested for in queries (b) and (c) is communication made to Supt Tan in official confidence. As such, there is no necessity for this Court to inspect any documents to determine this issue. That means it is for Supt Tan to decide whether public interest would suffer by the disclosure of the communication. Supt Tan has affirmed an affidavit stating that he is of the view that public interest would suffer if the information in queries (b) and (c) were to be disclosed. In this regard, the Defence has not shown that Supt Tan’s opinion is irrational in the Wednesbury sense, therefore Supt Tan is not compelled to testify on queries (b) and (c) because the information is protected under section 126 of the Evidence Act.

In any event, I am of the view that the information in queries (a) to (c) is not relevant or necessary for these proceedings. Whether the complainant complied with the SOP or not will not go towards proving or disproving the elements of the charge, for example. So, the Defence may therefore wish to focus its attention on the elements of the charge. But, of course, I leave it to Mr. Liew and his counsel as to how they wish to run their case.

Having ruled that Supt Tan is not compelled to testify on queries (b) and (c), that leaves us with query (a), which AGC agrees Supt Tan is able to give evidence on from his personal knowledge. AGC pointed out that Supt Tan has provided the information in his affidavit and submits that there is no necessity for Supt. Tan to testify.

So, that being the case, may I ascertain from the Defence Counsel as to whether he still requires Supt Tan to take the witness stand, and if so, for what purpose?

117    Ultimately the Defence decided not to call the CO to the stand because the CO had confirmed in his affidavit that there were SOPs in force.

Conclusion

118    On the totality of the evidence, I was satisfied that the Prosecution had proven the charge against the accused beyond a reasonable doubt, so I found him guilty and convicted him accordingly.

Antecedents

119    The accused had a clean record.

Prescribed punishment

120    The prescribed punishment for an offence under s 353 of the Penal Code was an imprisonment term which may extend to 4 years, or with fine, or with both.

Sentencing principles

121    In my view, given the nature and gravity of a s 353 Penal Code offence, the sentencing principles would be that of deterrence and retribution.

Applicable sentencing framework

122    The applicable sentencing framework is laid down by Justice See Kee Oon in Aw Soy Tee v Public Prosecutor [2020] SGHC 114 (“Aw Soy Tee”) which applies to police officers and public servants who are performing duties akin to police duties.

123    Justice See established the following presumptive sentencing ranges for first-time offenders who claim trial: at [30].

Category

Circumstances

Sentencing Band

1

Lesser harm and lower culpability

Fine or up to three months’ imprisonment

2

Greater harm and lower culpability or

Lesser harm and higher culpability

Three to eighteen months’ imprisonment

3

Greater harm and higher culpability

Eighteen months to four years’ imprisonment



124    See J emphasized that fines would only be imposed in exceptional cases which lie at the lowest end of the low-harm, low-culpability spectrum. See J held that the starting tariff is a short custodial sentence for offences under s 353 of the PC: at [53]. A non-exhaustive list of factors which might potentially influence the level of harm and/or culpability may be found at [24] of Aw Soy Tee: [29].

125    After determining the appropriate sentencing band using the harm-culpability matrix, See J held that further adjustments should be made to take into consideration other relevant aggravating and mitigating factors, which may take the starting sentence out of the applicable presumptive sentencing range:[31].

Parties’ sentencing positions

126    The Prosecution submitted that this case fell under Category 2 of Aw Soy Tee. It urged the court to impose a deterrent and retributive sentence of between four to six months’ imprisonment.

127    The Defence contended that this case came under Category 1 and argued that a fine would be adequate without suggesting a quantum.

Analysis of harm and culpability

128    In my view, the applicable harm and culpability factors were as follows:

(a)     The victim suffered minor injuries [note: 93].

(b)     The accused had used a dangerous means/implement namely a car in the present case;

(c)     The accused was a mature man, 52 years of age at the time of the offence. There was no evidence that he was suffering from any mental disorder when he committed the offence.

(d)     The offence arose because the accused was unhappy that the victim had blocked his way home by stopping a black Audi on the main road near the entrance of the Condominium where he was residing thereby causing obstruction and heavy congestion. He first horned at the victim to register his displeasure followed by a gesture to the victim to imply that the victim had not used his brains. Thereafter the accused snubbed the victim when the victim was trying to engage him by winding up the Car window and moving off, demonstrating his contempt for the victim’s authority as a police officer.

(e)     The accused committed the offence at about 7.50pm on a public road near a Condominium within public view and hearing at a time when traffic was getting heavy, and residents were returning to the Condominium. He repeatedly defied the victim. There were at least two eyewitnesses, PW4 Chua and PW5 Cindy who saw the entire incident. In these circumstances, there was prospect of possible erosion of public respect for the authority of the police.

(f)     The accused drove forward and collided into the victim not once but thrice displaying callous disregard for the victim’s safety.

(g)     The accused rendered no assistance even after the victim had fallen onto the Car’s bonnet on both occasions.

129    Having regard to the above factors, I agreed with the Prosecution that this was a Category 2 case of lesser harm and higher culpability with an indicative sentencing range of between three to eighteen months’ imprisonment. I disagreed with the Defence that the case qualified as a Category 1 case because the Defence had downplayed the accused’s culpability by reiterating that his actions were spurred by his anxiety and panic in the midst of a highly stressful situation and that he never went out of his way to deliberately defy police authority[note: 94].

Aggravating and mitigating factors

130    I next considered whether there were any other aggravating and/or mitigating factors which warranted a departure from this presumptive sentencing range.

131    There were no relevant mitigating factors. While the accused was a first offender, this was a neutral factor: BPH v Public Prosecutor and another appeal [2019] 2 SLR 764 at [85]. Since he did not plead guilty, there would also be no sentencing discount.

132    On the other hand, I agreed with the Prosecution that the accused had displayed no remorse as evident from his unfounded allegations[note: 95]:

(a)     Casting aspersions on the victim by alleging that the victim was out to frame the accused by his false FIR and statement. In this regard, the POHA charge was never preferred against the accused.

(b)     Blaming the victim for causing the first collision by “pausing” when it was caused by the accused who persisted in moving the Car forward.

(c)     Blaming the victim for standing in front of the Car, that “if the [victim] had been in his right mind, and he wanted to stop the vehicle, he should not be standing in front of the vehicle.

(d)     Accusing the Police and AGC of covering up the victim’s alleged offence of giving a false statement to the police.

133    Taking in account the aggravating factor above, I was of the view that a sentence of four months’ imprisonment which would be at the lower end of the applicable sentencing band would be appropriate. In calibrating the sentence, I had considered the two days that the accused spent in remand from his date of arrest on 14 August 2018 to 16 August 2018 when he was released on bail.

Sentencing precedents

134    The Prosecution cited five post Aw Soy Tee precedents which were all Category 1 cases. Imprisonments terms ranging from two weeks to four weeks were imposed in four cases, one involving throwing torn pieces of summons at the public servant and the rest for pushing the public servant. The sole case where a fine of $6,000 was imposed pertained to a single impulsive push.

135    The Defence cited numerous precedents consisting of dated pre-Aw Soy Tee precedents where fines were imposed[note: 96]. In Aw Soy Tee, See J cautioned that the framework is intended to reflect current sentencing practices so greater weight should be given to contemporary sentencing trends: [39]. The Defence referred to two post-Aw Soy Tee precedents which were Category 1 cases where sentences ranging from three weeks’ imprisonment to six weeks’ imprisonment along with a fine of $6,000 were imposed for single acts of pushing.

136    As evident from the post-Aw Soy Tee precedents cited by the parties, a custodial sentence is the norm, in line with what has been laid down in Aw Soy Tee.

137    The present case fell under Category 2 and involved the use of a moving car where the potential harm was far greater. The sentence should be higher to reflect the higher levels of harm and culpability.

Conclusion

138    In conclusion, the sentence of four months’ imprisonment was appropriate, and it gave effect to the principles of deterrence and retribution.

139    The accused is on bail pending appeal.

Case of rash act. TPO stopped one violator at left of 2 lanes for check, however another car stopped behind TPO saying TPO got no brain to stop along the road. While TPO asking the car to reserve (sic), the driver seem reluctantly and moved forward and hit onto TPO.

[4]: The said driver then gestured to me, by pointing his right index finger to his right temple, after which he use his right palm and wave it in a horizontal motion. The victim told the court that the accused made a “no brain” gesture. He confirmed that the accused did not verbally say to the victim the words recorded in the FIR and statement.

The victim clarified that his FIR and statement were given to the best of his recollection.

It was evident from the in-car camera footage in P4 (V1) that the accused did not utter those words. In my view, it was not a material discrepancy. Although the accused did not verbalise the message, the victim had seen the accused giving the victim a hand gesture and had perceived the accused to be saying that the victim had no brain for stopping near the entrance of the Condominium thus blocking traffic. In that regard, the victim had been consistent in his perception in his FIR, statement and court evidence.

[5]: I then instructed the said driver to reverse and stop inside the bus bay for me to conduct a check on him ……………..

Initially the victim told the court that he had asked the accused to reverse to the bus layby/bay[note: 100]. The victim subsequently clarified that he only told the accused to reverse and did not expressly indicate to the accused to reverse into the bus bay[note: 101].

The victim explained that he had given his statement based on his recollection before he watched the video footages in P4. After watching the video footages, he confirmed that he did not specify where the accused was to reverse to[note: 102].

The victim had given a fair explanation. He told the court that his intention was to guide the accused to reverse to the bus bay[note: 103] but he did not get the chance to do so because the accused started to drive off[note: 104].

The victim testified that he had to walk at a fast pace from the accused’s driver door to get to the front of the Car when the accused started to drive off[note: 105].

The victim agreed that he did not run to the front of the Car. He explained it was a wrong choice of word.

The victim gave his statement without the benefit of the in-car camera footages. It was an immaterial discrepancy. While the victim did not run, he had to walk briskly, faster than his normal pace to catch up to the front of the moving Car[note: 106].

Interestingly in the accused’s statement exhibit D9, page 2, first paragraph, he stated “…. I wind up the driver side window and because I was panicking, my vehicle went forward. That Traffic Police Officer then “ran to the front of my vehicle and tap the bonnet area, ….”. The accused himself clearly perceived the victim as having run to the front of the Car driver window to the front of the Car too.

As such, it would be fair to say that the victim did not exaggerate or embellish in his statement when he narrated that he then ran to the front of the Car because that was how things seemed and felt then.

[5]: I then run to the front of the said vehicle, pointing my left palm out towards the said driver, as a stop sign and also verbal command to stop his vehicle.

The victim agreed that the video footage (P4 V1) did not capture him pointing his palm outwards as a “stop” sign. It showed him moving his hand up and down with his palm facing downwards[note: 107].

The victim said he had no explanation[note: 108]. He had earlier testified that pointing the palm outwards was the “Stop” sign he was taught[note: 109]. The actual “Stop” gesture captured in the in-car camera footages where he was seen moving his hand up and down with his palm facing downwards was what he could manage to the best of his ability to signal to the accused to stop then as he shuffled to the front of the Car[note: 110].

It was a minor discrepancy. The victim was trying his best to signal to the accused to stop even as the victim was shuffling to the front of the Car to stop the accused from moving off. In that situation, it was understandable that the victim could not display the perfect “stop” gesture.

The victim testified that he did not verbally command the accused to stop at the time when he was shuffling to the front of the Car from the accused’s driver window[note: 111].

The victim explained that he gave his statement to the best of his recollection because it was a hectic situation[note: 112]. With the benefit of the video footages, he confirmed that at that juncture, he did not give any verbal instruction to the accused to stop[note: 113].

This was a minor discrepancy. Even if the victim did not verbally command the accused to stop at that time, he had gestured to the accused to stop.
